	                    Officer scoops Community Policing award


	                    <span id="Template_ctl08_lblMessage"><font color="Red"></font></span>

	                </h1>
                	
<p class="MsoBodyText"><img width="304" alt="Seargent Scott Meechan accepting community award" class="BorderImageRight" title="Seargent Scott Meechan accepting community award" src="/images/pc-scott-meechan-award.gif" style="MARGIN: 15px" height="260"/>A Lothian and
Borders Police officer has won a national award for his services to
community policing.<br />
<br />
Sergeant Scott Meechan was honoured on Thursday 3<sup>rd</sup>
November at the Jane&rsquo;s Police Review Gala Awards in London, where
Home Secretary Theresa May gave the keynote speech and presented
the awards.<br />
<br />
The event, which was held at the London Hilton in Park Lane and
hosted by sports broadcaster and Strictly Come Dancing winner Chris
Hollins, recognised the achievements of police officers from all
over Britain as they contested six award categories.<br />
<br />
Sergeant Meechan was presented with the prize for Community Police
Officer of the Year for his diligent work to improve facilities and
make positive differences in communities throughout
Midlothian.<br />
<br />
Last year, Lothian and Borders Police delivered a promise to its
communities to provide a visible and engaging police presence
throughout Edinburgh, the Lothians and the Scottish Borders.<br />
<br />
Community Commitment was initiated in September 2010 and the
Pathhead Village Hall was chosen as the ideal location to host the
launch as it epitomised the benefits of engagement between police
and communities.<br />
<br />
After listening to concerns of members of the public in Pathhead,
Sergeant Meechan and his team established that antisocial behaviour
issues in the area could be attributed to a lack of resources and
facilities for local youths.<br />
<br />
Improving the conditions of the village hall was identified as a
priority and Sergeant Meechan sought and secured funding from IKEA
Edinburgh for redevelopment of the hall, which is now regularly
used by all members of the Pathhead community.<br />
<br />
Speaking after receiving his prize, Sergeant Scott Meechan said: "I
am extremely honoured and humbled to have won this incredible
award.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
"Community Policing is vital for establishing and building on our
relationship with the public and it is important we listen to the
needs and concerns of our communities so we can address them
accordingly. IKEA, and in particular, Liz Stanton, IKEA's Community
Education Support Specialist, were fantastic throughout.&nbsp; Liz
and the other staff were completely supportive of what we were
trying to achieve and did all they could to help."<br />
<br />
<span class="emailstyle15">Sergeant Meechan was also instrumental
in the Top Service, Seed to Soup Project, which assists young
people who are experiencing difficulties in mainstream
schooling.<br />
<br />
The young people are involved in developing a garden, harvesting
the produce and learning to cook the crop.<br />
<br />
Sergeant Meechan used his local business contacts to secure free
goods and services, establish an SQA qualification and develop a
work experience programme.<br />
<br /></span>Sergeant Meechan said: "All of our work proves that
community spirit is still alive and kicking, it sometimes just
needs something positive to happen to bring everyone
together."<br />
<br />
<span class="emailstyle15">Chief Superintendent Mark Williams,
Divisional Commander for East and Midlothian said: "The work
undertaken by Scott and his team is nothing short of
miraculous.<br />
<br />
"To have secured such substantial funding for the refurbishment of
Pathhead Village Hall and to have united the local community in
improving their village has already proven to be a great
success.<br />
<br />
"His work in the Seed to Soup project has been hugely beneficial in
breaking down barriers. The programme developed has given a sense
of hope and achievement to some of Midlothian&rsquo;s hardest to reach
young people and transformed the way they engage with the
Police.<br />
<br />
"Lothian and Borders Police are committed to working alongside
local residents, business and our partner agencies to address any
issues or concerns raised within our communities and deliver a
suitable and appropriate solution.<br />
<br />
"Scott&rsquo;s award is recognition of the success we are achieving in
that respect.&rdquo;</span></p>
